    {
      "url": "https://askiso.iso-ne.com/s/article/Tips-for-submitting-a-Transitional-Cluster-Study-Agreement-package",
      "title": "Tips for submitting a Transitional Cluster Study Agreement package",
      "text": "Tips for submitting a Transitional Cluster Study Agreement package\n\nLoading\n\n### Information\n\nTitle\n\nTips for submitting a Transitional Cluster Study Agreement package\n\nContent\n\nIf you have a valid Interconnection Request that does not have a completed System Impact Study prior to August 12, 2024, you can expect to receive a Transitional Cluster Study Agreement. The deadline to submit your fully executed Transitional Cluster Study Agreement (TCS Agreement) package with all required items to the ISO is October 10, 2025. A fully executed TCS Agreement package must contain the following materials:\n\n- Executed TCS Agreement\n- Selection of Interconnection Service\n- Study deposit (cash only)\n- Commercial readiness deposit (cash or letter of credit)\n- 100% site control\n- All required technical data\n\nDon’t wait for receipt of a Transitional Cluster Study Agreement to start completing your study package! Interconnection requests without a fully executed and complete Transitional Cluster Study Agreement package by October 10, 2025 will be withdrawn from the interconnection queue, without further opportunity to cure. Interconnection Requests withdrawn before the start of the TCS will not be subject to a withdrawal penalty. In addition to these requirements, there are also administrative tasks which take time:\n\n- To access interconnection request critical energy infrastructure information (IR CEII), you must request this access, which can take up to two weeks. Visit the Request CEII Access page on the ISO website for instructions.\n- To submit materials via the Interconnection Request Tracking Tool (IRTT) software, you must have a user account that has been assigned to the interconnection request and has been assigned the appropriate role. For help, view the How to create accounts in the Interconnection Request Tracking Tool knowledge article.\n- You must have an ISO Customer ID, and the Company Name associated with your Customer ID must match across all ISO registrations, submissions, and systems, including the interconnection customer listed on the interconnection request. Complete and submit the Request Generation Interconnect Customer ID form to get an ISO Customer ID.\n\n## Resources\n\n- Visit the Order No. 2023 Key Project page on the ISO website\n- Read the Interconnection Process Guide on the ISO website\n- View the 2025 Interim Reconfiguration Auction Qualification Process timeline\n- View the ISO Public Generator Interconnection Queue\n- View ISO-NE Planning Procedure 5-6\n- Read Section II, ISO New England Open Access Transmission Tariff(OATT)\n- Read Schedule 22, Large Generator Interconnection Procedures(LGIPs)\n- Read Schedule 23, Small Generator Interconnection Procedures(SGIPs)\n- Read Schedule 25, Elective Transmission Upgrade Interconnection Procedures(ETUs)\n\nLast Modified Date\n\n6/9/2025 2:15 PM\n\nURL Name\n\nTips-for-submitting-a-Transitional-Cluster-Study-Agreement-package\n\nInterconnection Tariff, Rules, Procedures & Manuals\n\nDrop Files\n\nUpload FilesOr drop files\n\n## Trending Articles\n\n- How to pick-up a digital certificate\n- How to import (install) a digital certificate to use in Chrome or Edge\n- Doing Business with ISO New England (self-paced training)\n- CROW Sandbox for New Will Hold CSO Capacity Supply Obligation Designation\n- Changes to CAMS Asset Email Lists Effective June 9, 2026\n\nLoading\n\nTips for submitting a Transitional Cluster Study Agreement package",
