      "text": "Interconnection Technical Notice\n\nProviding Proof of Regulatory Limitations As a Demonstration of Site Control \nBackground \nThis notice addresses the requirements related to Site Control for purposes of the \ninterconnection of Generating Facilities and Elective Transmission Upgrades (ETU) seeking to \nparticipate in a Cluster Study, including the Transitional Cluster Study. This notice adds \nadditional detail to the requirements in Section 3.4.2 of Schedule 22 – Large Generator \nInterconnection Procedures and Schedule 23 – Small Generator Interconnection Procedures, \nand Section 3.3.2 in Schedule 25 – ETU Interconnection Procedures of the ISO’s Open Access \nTransmission Tariff. These requirements will be incorporated into ISO-NE Planning Procedure \nNo. 5-6 through a future update to that planning procedure. \nDemonstration of Site Control \nTo demonstrate Site Control, an Interconnection Customer must submit documentation that \nestablishes the exclusive right to develop, construct, operate, and maintain the Generating \nFacility or terminal location(s) of an ETU over the term of expected operation. The Site Control \nmust be of sufficient size to construct and operate the Generating Facility or terminal \nlocation(s) of the ETU and Interconnection Customer must provide documentation establishing \none of the following: (a) that Interconnection Customer is the owner in fee simple of the real \nproperty or holds an easement for which new interconnection is sought; (b) that \nInterconnection Customer holds a valid written leasehold or other contractual interest in the \nreal property for which new interconnection is sought; (c) that Interconnection Customer holds \na valid written option to purchase or a leasehold interest in the real property for which new \ninterconnection is sought; (d) that Interconnection Customer holds a duly executed written \ncontract to purchase, acquire an easement, a license or a leasehold interest in the real \nproperty for which new interconnection is sought; or (e) that Interconnection Customer has \nfiled applications for required permits to site on federal or state property. See Schedules 22, \n23, and 25 – Definitions, Site Control. \n\nTiming to Demonstrate Site Control and Submission Requirements \nInterconnection Customers must submit their Site Control documents as part of their \nInterconnection Request through IRTT during the Cluster Request Window. 1(Schedules 22 and \n23, Section 3.4.2 and 25, Section 3.3.2 – Initiating an Interconnection Request). Within 5 \nBusiness Days of receipt of an Interconnection Request, pursuant to Section 3.4.4 of \nSchedules 22 and 23, and Section 3.3.4 of 25, ISO-NE will notify the Interconnection Customer \nthat its Interconnection Request is valid or identify any deficiencies which includes deficiencies \nrelated to Site Control. \nAll Interconnection Customers must demonstrate 100% Site Control for the Generating Facility \nor terminal location(s) of an ETU when requesting Capacity Network Resource Interconnection \nService or Capacity Network Import Interconnection Service without exception. \nAll Interconnection Customers must demonstrate 100% Site Control for the Generating Facility \nor terminal location(s) of an ETU when requesting Network Resource Interconnection Service or \nNetwork Import Interconnection Service, unless Regulatory Limitations prevent such a \ndemonstration. In cases where a Regulatory Limitation is claimed, the Interconnection \nCustomer must also provide the following items with their Interconnection Request submission \nfor a Cluster Study: 2 \n• a signed attestation from an officer of the company; \n• documentation sufficiently describing and explaining the source and effects of such regulatory limitations, including a description of any conditions that must be met to satisfy the regulatory limitations and the anticipated time by which Interconnection Customer expects to satisfy the regulatory requirements; and \n• a cash deposit in lieu of Site Control of $10,000 per MW, subject to a minimum of $500,000 and a maximum of $2,000,000. Demonstration of a Regulatory Limitation A Regulatory Limitation is a federal, state, local, or Tribal law (as defined in Schedules 22, 23, and 25 of the OATT) which makes it infeasible to obtain Site Control prior to an Interconnection Customer’s submission of its Interconnection Request. For example, a Regulatory Limitation could be a federal, state, local and/or Tribal law that requires a validated ISO-NE Interconnection Request before an Interconnection Customer may obtain necessary land rights to demonstrate Site Control. A Regulatory Limitation is not intended to include permitting or siting issues. To demonstrate a Regulatory Limitation, an Interconnection Customer must also submit the following with the Site Control Deposit: \n1 For the Transitional Cluster Study, Site Control documentation for 100% of the proposed Generating Facility or ETU must be \nprovided when Interconnection Customer returns the Transitional Cluster Study Agreement. \n2 For the Transitional Cluster Study, there is no ability for Interconnection Customers to provide documentation and cash depos its \nin place of demonstrating Site Control when a Regulatory Limitation exists. \n\n• a signed affidavit from an officer of the company indicating that Site Control is unobtainable due to Regulatory Limitations as the term is defined by the ISO-NE; and \n• documentation sufficiently describing and explaining the source and effects of such Regulatory Limitations, including a description of any condition that must be met to satisfy the Regulatory Limitations and the anticipated time by which the Interconnection Customer expects to satisfy the regulatory restrictions. ISO-NE will determine whether the Interconnection Customer has demonstrated that a qualifying Regulatory Limitation exists during the Cluster Request Window. If ISO-NE determines that that there is a Regulatory Limitation, ISO-NE will hold the Site Control Deposit until the Interconnection Customer provides the required Site Control demonstration for its project in the Cluster Study Process. The Interconnection Customer must demonstrate full Site Control for the Generating Facility or terminal location(s) of an ETU within 180 Calendar Days of the effective date of executing an Interconnection Agreement. See Schedules 22 and 23 Section 3.4.2 and 25, Section 3.3.2. \n\n",
