188 FERC ¶ 61,134 (2024).\n\n4ISO New England Inc., 191 FERC ¶ 61,018 (2025) (April Compliance Order).\n\nOrder Nos. 2023 and 2023-A and with the Commission’s directives in the April Compliance Order. Accordingly, we accept the Second Compliance Filing, effective August 12, 2024, as requested. 5\n\n## I. Background\n\nOrder Nos. 2023 and 2023-A require all public utility transmission providers to adopt revised pro forma LGIPs, pro forma LGIAs, pro forma SGIPs, and pro forma SGIAs. 6 These revisions ensure that interconnection customers are able to interconnect to the transmission system in a reliable, efficient, transparent, and timely manner, and will prevent undue discrimination. 7 In Order No. 2023, the Commission adopted a comprehensive package of reforms in three general categories: (1) reforms to implement a first-ready, first-served cluster study process; (2) reforms to increase the speed of interconnection queue processing; and (3) reforms to incorporate technological advancements into the interconnection process.\n\nOn May 14, 2024, in Docket No. ER24-2009-000, the Filing Parties 8 in that case submitted proposed revisions to the ISO-NE Tariff to comply with the requirements of Order No. 2023 (First Compliance Filing). 9 In the April Compliance Order, the Commission found that Filing Parties’ First Compliance Filing partially complied with the requirements of Order Nos. 2023 and 2023-A. Accordingly, the Commission\n\n5 See infra app. A (providing eTariff records).\n\n6 The pro forma LGIP and pro forma LGIA establish the terms and conditions under which public utilities that own, control, or operate facilities for transmitting energy in interstate commerce must provide interconnection service to generating facilities larger than 20 MW. The pro forma SGIP and pro forma SGIA establish the terms and conditions under which public utilities that own, control, or operate facilities for transmitting energy in interstate commerce must provide interconnection service to generating facilities no larger than 20 MW. Order No. 2023, 184 FERC ¶ 61,054 at P 2.\n\n7Id. P 1.\n\n8 The filing parties that submitted the First Compliance Filing in Docket No. ER24-2009-000 also included the New England Power Pool (NEPOOL). Noting this difference, for simplicity this order refers to the filing parties in either proceeding as “Filing Parties.”\n\n9 Filing Parties also submitted a companion filing consisting of revisions not directly required by Order Nos. 2023 and 2023-A in Docket No. ER24-2007-000. The April Compliance Order addressed and accepted the proposed revisions submitted in Docket No. ER24-2007-000.\n\nDocket No. ER24-2009-001 - 3 accepted Filing Parties’ First Compliance Filing in part, effective August 12, 2024, and directed the Filing Parties to submit a further compliance filing within 60 days of the issuance of the April Compliance Order. Specifically, the Commission directed further revisions to ISO-NE’s Tariff to comply with the following requirements of Order Nos. 2023 and 2023-A: cluster study process, allocation of cluster network upgrade costs, site control, commercial readiness, LGIA deposit, transition process, elimination of reasonable efforts, affected system study process and modeling requirements, affected system pro forma agreements, and modeling and ride-through requirements for non-synchronous generating facilities. 10\n\nII. Second Compliance Filing\n\nFiling Parties state that through the Second Compliance Filing they propose revisions to ISO-NE Tariff section I.2.2, Tariff Schedules 11, 22 (ISO-NE LGIP), 23 (ISO-NE SGIP), and Tariff section III.13 in compliance with the April Compliance Order. Filing Parties also state that they have made conforming changes to the ISO-NE SGIP and Tariff Schedule 25 (Elective Transmission Upgrade Interconnection Procedures) 11 consistent with the directives of the April Compliance Order.\n\n10 April Compliance Order, 191 FERC ¶ 61,018 at PP 77, 85, 100, 102, 133, 135, 152-153, 158, 186, 197, 218, 227, 280-283.\n\n11 Schedule 25 contains interconnection requirements for Elective Transmission Upgrades. The Tariff defines an “Elective Transmission Upgrade” as follows:\n\nElective Transmission Upgrade . . . shall mean a new Pool Transmission Facility, Merchant Transmission Facility or Other Transmission Facility that is interconnecting to the Administered Transmission System, or an upgrade to an existing Pool Transmission Facility, Merchant Transmission Facility or Other Transmission Facility that is part of or interconnected to the Administered Transmission System for which the Interconnection Customer has agreed to pay all of the costs of said Elective Transmission Upgrade and of any additions or modifications to the Administered Transmission System that are required to accommodate the Elective Transmission Upgrade. An Elective Transmission Upgrade is not a Generator Interconnection Related Upgrade, a Regional Transmission Upgrade, or a Market Efficiency Transmission Upgrade.\n\nTariff, § II, Schedule 25 (12.0.0), § 1 (Definitions), Elective Transmission Upgrade.\n\nFiling Parties request that the proposed Tariff revisions become effective on August 12, 2024. 12\n\nIII. Notice of Filing and Responsive Pleadings\n\nNotice of Filing Parties’ Second Compliance Filing was published in the Federal Register, 90 Fed. Reg. 24275 (June 9, 2025), with comments, interventions, and protests due on or before June 24, 2025. NEPOOL filed supportive comments requesting that the Commission accept the Second Compliance Filing without delay, condition, or modification. 13\n\n## IV. Discussion\n\nAs discussed below, we find that Filing Parties’ Second Compliance Filing complies with the requirements of Order Nos. 2023 and 2023-A. Accordingly, we accept Filing Parties’ Second Compliance Filing, effective August 12, 2024, as requested.\n\nWe find that Filing Parties have complied with the following directives from the April Compliance Order by largely proposing 